---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Breadcrumbs from "../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro";

const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.endsWith("/")
  ? import.meta.env.BASE_URL
  : `${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Methodology | How Much Music"
  description="How How Much Music models annual earnings ranges, separates gross and artist-side estimates, and reviews pages before indexing."
  type="article"
>
  <Breadcrumbs items={[
    { label: "Home", href: baseUrl },
    { label: "Insights", href: `${baseUrl}insights/` },
    { label: "Methodology" }
  ]} />

  <section>
    <p class="eyebrow">Methodology</p>
    <h1>How earnings are modeled</h1>
    <p class="page-updated">Updated June 18, 2026</p>
    <p>
      The estimates use conservative modeled ranges, not audited royalty statements. The goal is to
      make catalog economics legible without pretending to have access to private contracts.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="quick-answer-card" aria-labelledby="methodology-quick-answer-title">
    <p class="eyebrow">Quick Answer</p>
    <h2 id="methodology-quick-answer-title">The number is a conservative annual range.</h2>
    <p>
      A page starts with public context, then separates gross catalog activity from the smaller
      artist-side or estate-side share when the available information supports that split.
    </p>
  </section>

  <nav class="page-jump-list" aria-label="Methodology sections">
    <a href="#methodology-represents">What estimates represent</a>
    <a href="#methodology-ready">Ready for readers</a>
    <a href="#methodology-sources">Source labels</a>
    <a href="#methodology-rankings">Rankings</a>
    <a href="#methodology-uncertainty">Uncertainty</a>
  </nav>

  <section id="methodology-represents">
    <h2>What the estimates represent</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Artist and song pages use conservative annual earnings ranges as editorial estimates.</li>
      <li>Where possible, pages separate gross catalog revenue from the artist-side retained share.</li>
      <li>Ownership notes explain when labels, publishers, estates, or catalog buyers likely absorb a large part of the revenue.</li>
      <li>Headline artist-side ranges are intentionally discounted against aggressive top-line assumptions, because public stream counts rarely reveal contract splits, geography, ad-supported share, or recoupment.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="methodology-ready">
    <h2>What makes a page ready for readers</h2>
    <p>
      A reviewed page needs enough structured context to answer the reader's question without
      leaning on repeated generic copy.
    </p>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Song pages need a page-specific article entry, ownership context, platform references, artwork, related songs, and separated gross and artist-side revenue fields.</li>
      <li>Artist pages need a page-specific article entry, structured catalog earnings, ownership context, top-song support, and visible public references.</li>
      <li>Pages with limited context are not promoted as reviewed editorial pages.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="methodology-sources">
    <h2>How source labels should be read</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li><strong>Platform identity</strong> links confirm public song or artist identity on listening platforms.</li>
      <li><strong>Release metadata</strong> links support track, album, artwork, or release context.</li>
      <li><strong>Certification context</strong> links show public certification-scale context where available.</li>
      <li><strong>Ownership context</strong> links support catalog, master, publishing, or rights-control discussion where available.</li>
      <li>No source label should be read as proof of a private royalty statement unless the source itself discloses royalty data.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="example-card" aria-labelledby="methodology-example-title">
    <p class="eyebrow">Example</p>
    <h2 id="methodology-example-title">Why two popular songs can show different ranges</h2>
    <p>
      A newer streaming hit, a seasonal standard, and a song with durable sync licensing potential
      can all produce different annual value patterns. The model is more useful when it explains
      those differences instead of flattening every play into one public per-stream number.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="methodology-rankings">
    <h2>How rankings work</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Rankings use the midpoint of the displayed revenue range.</li>
      <li>Album rankings aggregate the tracked songs currently covered, not the whole commercial album unless every track is covered.</li>
      <li>That makes the rankings useful for comparison, not as a substitute for accounting data.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section id="methodology-uncertainty">
    <h2>What still introduces uncertainty</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Legacy contract terms are rarely public.</li>
      <li>Catalog-sale details can materially alter the performer or estate share.</li>
      <li>Streaming mix, geography, and licensing activity change over time.</li>
      <li>Platform-reported play counts do not map cleanly to take-home earnings, so lower directional ranges are favored over maximum-case estimates.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="related-reading-card" aria-labelledby="methodology-sources-title">
    <h2 id="methodology-sources-title">Useful background</h2>
    <p>These links explain parts of the public music-economics context; they do not verify any single estimate on this site.</p>
    <div class="related-link-row">
      <a href="https://loudandclear.byspotify.com/">Spotify Loud &amp; Clear</a>
      <a href="https://www.riaa.com/u-s-sales-database/">RIAA revenue database</a>
      <a href="https://www.copyright.gov/music-modernization/">U.S. Copyright Office: Music Modernization Act</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
